            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Never&lt;/i&gt; issue a 301 unless you &lt;i&gt;mean it&lt;/i&gt;. 301 means permanent, and permanent means &lt;i&gt;permanent&lt;/i&gt;, meaning it will be cached by user agents, meaning long, caffeine-filled nights staring at application logs wondering if you&apos;re going insane because you swear some page should have been called or updated and you swear to God it works on your machine but not the client&apos;s.   If you absolutely must call a 301, put a cache-control max-age on the resource. You don&apos;t have infinite wisdom and you shouldn&apos;t be acting like you do.&lt;/span&gt;

