                        &lt;/span&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;

            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;But browsers that respect the header will leave the page and close the connection while your script is still executing. This is totally bad. PHP will go on with the script for some time (that&apos;s why your code executes) but may abort it randomly in the middle of execution, leaving stuff broken. Calling ignore_user_abort() will prevent this, but sincerely I it&apos;s not worth it. Just go on with your HTML writing stuff (though probably useless) but don&apos;t do stuff that writes on disk or database after a header(&apos;Location:&apos;); Write to disk before the redirect if possible. [Also: url should be absolute.]&lt;/span&gt;

